Title: Body of Water
Description: A natural and geographical feature of the earth's surface that is covered with water, such as a lake, river, stream or ocean.

Title: Reservoir
Description: A body of water, such as a man-made pond or lake, that is used for the retention and regulation of water.

Title: Waterfall
Description: A body of water where a flow of water, such as a mountain stream or river, falls over a steep incline or vertical drop.

Title: Bay-Harbor
Description: A coastal body of water where ships can safely anchor.

Title: River
Description: A body of water, usually containing fresh water, that generally flows through land and empties into an ocean, lake, river or other body of water.

Title: Canal
Description: An artificial waterway constructed for shipping, irrigation or recreational usage.

Title: Lake
Description: A large body of water that may contain fresh water or salt water. A lake is larger than a pond and must be regionally recognized. Lakes are generally separated from the ocean by land.

Title: Mountain or Hill
Description: A natural and geographical feature that is higher than the surrounding land. Places in this category must be regionally recognized.

Title: Mountain Passes
Description: A route through a mountain range or over a ridge. Mountain passes must be regionally recognized.

Title: Mountain Peaks
Description: A summit or top of a mountain. Mountain peaks must be regionally recognized.

Title: Undersea Feature
Description: A natural or artificial feature that is below sea level. For example, coral reef barrier, ship wreck and more. Places in this category must be regionally recognized.

Title: Forest, Heath or Other Vegetation
Description: A dense growth of trees, open uncultivated land or other large masses of vegetation.

Title: Natural and Geographical
Description: A feature not classified as a Body of Water (350-3500), Mountain or Hill (350-3510), Undersea Feature (350-3520), or Forest, Heath or Other Vegetation (350-3522).
